g.text: Chromatic Aberration
Chromatic aberration is an optical phenomenon
that occurs when a lens is unable to focus all
colors of the spectrum onto a single point. This
results in a distorted image, with the edges of
objects appearing to be fringed with color.
It is particularly noticeable in photographs taken
with low-quality lenses or when using a lens at its
widest aperture setting
It can be corrected using a lens with a more
complex curvature, or by using multiple lenses in
a system known as a chromatic corrector
Vignetting
Vignetting refers to the phenomenon in which the
corners of an image appear darker than the
center.
This is usually caused by the physical constraints
of the lens or camera, such as the shape of the
aperture or the presence of obstructions in the
optical path
